{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537192"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:14:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:14:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15912"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15912"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.04,0.17,0.18,0.47]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8603"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63114"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8603","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8603"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15912"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48565"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"16"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20607"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63114","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63114"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic interested in participating in a clinical trial for a new antihypertensive medication. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She exercises regularly and maintains a healthy diet. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The trial is described as a first-in-human study involving 30 participants to determine safety, tolerability, and pharmacokinetics of escalating single doses of the medication.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this type of clinical trial?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Phase 3 study","Phase 4 study","Pilot study","Phase 2 study","Phase 1 study"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario describes a classic \u003Cstrong\u003EPhase 1\u003C/strong\u003E clinical trial. These studies are typically first-in-human trials that focus on safety, tolerability, and pharmacokinetics of new drugs. They usually involve a small number of healthy volunteers (20-100) and often use dose-escalation protocols to determine the maximum tolerated dose. The primary aim is to understand how the drug behaves in the human body and to identify any immediate safety concerns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhase 2\u003C/strong\u003E studies focus on establishing preliminary efficacy and optimal dosing in patients with the target condition. They typically involve several hundred participants who have the condition the drug is intended to treat, which would not be appropriate for initial safety testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhase 3\u003C/strong\u003E trials are large-scale studies involving hundreds to thousands of patients to confirm efficacy, monitor side effects, and compare the drug to commonly used treatments. These trials only proceed after safety and preliminary efficacy have been established in earlier phases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhase 4\u003C/strong\u003E studies occur after a drug has been approved and is being marketed. They focus on long-term safety and effectiveness in the general population and may identify rare side effects not detected in earlier trials.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epilot study\u003C/strong\u003E is a small-scale preliminary study conducted to evaluate feasibility, time, cost, adverse events, and effect size in preparation for a larger study. While Phase 1 trials are sometimes considered pilot studies, this term is too general to accurately describe this specific type of clinical trial.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Phase 1 clinical trials primarily assess safety and pharmacokinetics in healthy volunteers","Phase 1 studies typically enroll a small number of participants (20-100)","Maximum tolerated dose is a key endpoint in phase 1 trials"],"references":["Umscheid CA, Margolis DJ, Grossman CE. Key concepts of clinical trials: a narrative review. Postgrad Med. 2011;123(5):194-204. doi:10.3810/pgm.2011.09.2475"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48565"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15912"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48565","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48565"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-20T02:55:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-20T02:56:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8603"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63114"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"16","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/16"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udcca","name":"Biostatistics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"